SIMPLE: slush
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Slush
<hw>Slush</hw> <pr>(sl⟦ucr⟧sh)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Sw.
<ets>slaska</ets> to paddle in water, <ets>slask</ets> wet,
filth.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also <asp>slosh</asp>.]</altsp>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Soft mud.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A mixture of snow and water; half-melted
snow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A soft mixture of grease and other materials, used
for lubrication.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The refuse grease and fat collected in cooking,
especially on shipboard.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>A mixture of white lead and lime,
with which the bright parts of machines, such as the connecting rods of
steamboats, are painted to be preserved from oxidation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slush</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Slush
<hw>Slush</hw> <pr>(sl⟦ucr⟧sh)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Slushed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Slushing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To smear
with slush or grease; <as>as, to <ex>slush</ex> a mast</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To paint with a mixture of white lead and
lime.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slushy</ent>⟦br⟧
